Why we made these changes
Background

When the Lambda connects to Aurora through RDS Proxy, three things must line up perfectly:

Component	Must matchLambda's DB_USER env var	↔
The username in the Secrets Manager secret registered to the Proxy	↔
The DB user in the Lambda's IAM policy resource ARN	↔

If any of the three disagree, the connection fails with an authentication error.

What the situation was

The DBA (CG) created:

A DB user in Aurora: pgsi_ans00315015
A Secrets Manager secret containing that user + password
Registered the secret with the RDS Proxy

But the Lambda code and IAM policy were still built to log in as an older service account:

Plain Text
1
DB_USER = "lambda_svc"
2
IAM policy → dbuser/lambda_svc
Show more lines

That mismatch caused two errors in sequence during our test today:

First error (before Change 1):

Plain Text
1
28000 FATAL — This RDS proxy has no credentials for the role lambda_svc.
Show more lines

Meaning: the Proxy has no secret containing username lambda_svc.

Second error (before Change 2):

Plain Text
1
28P01 FATAL — The IAM authentication failed for the role pgsi_ans00315015.
Show more lines

Meaning: the DB user was now correct, but the Lambda's IAM policy didn't grant rds-db:connect for that user.

Why the fixes solve it
Change 1 aligns the Lambda's DB_USER with the username stored in the Proxy's Secrets Manager secret so the Proxy can authenticate to Aurora on behalf of the Lambda.
Change 2 aligns the Lambda's IAM permission to allow rds-db:connect for the same DB user so the IAM auth token it generates is valid for that user.

Together, this makes the entire chain consistent:

Plain Text
1
Lambda (DB_USER = pgsi_ans00315015)
2
→ IAM policy allows rds-db:connect for pgsi_ans00315015
3
→ Proxy has a secret for pgsi_ans00315015
4
→ Proxy uses that secret to log in to Aurora
Show more lines
Why we didn't pick the alternative

The other option would have been to ask CG to:

Create a new DB user lambda_svc
Create a new Secrets Manager secret
Register it as an additional Auth entry on the Proxy

That would work, but:

Requires DB team coordination
Adds a second credential to rotate/manage
Doesn't match what CG already provisioned

Aligning the Lambda to the DBA-provisioned user is smaller, faster, and matches the existing infrastructure.
